50:12.760 --> 50:14.800
than the number of neurons, even the cell bodies,

50:14.800 --> 50:15.800
may be different sizes.

50:15.800 --> 50:18.320
Elephants and dolphins actually have bigger neuronal bodies

50:18.320 --> 50:20.040
than do many other animals.

50:20.040 --> 50:23.600
And we don't really know very much about even our brains now.

50:23.600 --> 50:25.280
But we've tended to make this assumption.

50:25.280 --> 50:28.640
It's almost like a religious or cosmological assumption

50:28.640 --> 50:30.880
that we are different from the rest of the animal world.

50:30.880 --> 50:33.640
We're at the top of the pinnacle, and everybody's below us.

50:33.640 --> 50:35.280
And nobody else is thinking, we're

50:35.280 --> 50:37.120
the only ones who think we're the only ones who

50:37.120 --> 50:38.320
communicate using language.

50:38.320 --> 50:41.200
And language, the word language, comes from the tongue.

50:41.200 --> 50:41.760
We have a tongue.

50:41.760 --> 50:45.760
We think about speech more than any other body language,

50:45.760 --> 50:47.400
as we said before.

50:47.400 --> 50:51.480
And as we're finding more and more

50:51.480 --> 50:53.120
details, as we're discovering more details

50:53.120 --> 50:55.800
about other animal systems, we see that there

50:55.800 --> 50:58.400
is more going on than we ever thought before,

50:58.400 --> 51:03.400
behaviorally, acoustically, in terms of sensory systems.

51:03.400 --> 51:06.680
And I just think we're kind of pompous at assuming

51:06.680 --> 51:09.560
that nobody else is out there thinking.

51:09.560 --> 51:13.360
The question used to be, do other animals think?

51:13.360 --> 51:15.120
And I think the question has shifted.

51:15.120 --> 51:17.240
